abstract: Experiments were performed at two time points in the 24hour cycle to determine whether isolated right atria of rats would vary in sensitivity, with a circadian rhythm, to two concentrations of acetylcholine. The beating rate of the atria decreased more in response to the drug if the atria were isolated at 1100 than if isolated at 2300 hours.

DIETARY use of raw kidney beans (Phaseolus vulgaris) is known to increase the incidence of liver necrosis in weanling rats1 and nutritional muscular dystrophy in chicks2. Although this effect has been attributed to some heat labile antagonist(s) to vitamin E, the nature of such antagonists and the mechanism of their action are unknown.

IN an earlier communication to Nature1 it was argued that the attempt to resolve the discrepancy in data on choice reaction time in relation to age in terms of the effective duration of signals2 must be regarded as inadequate. The observations were based on a small sample (N = 48) of data from a psycho-physiological study of the possible effects of ageing on professional (that is, airline, military and test) pilots. The present communication is a brief account of some of the further results obtained to date in a larger sample (N = 201).

WHILE studying the morphology of thiamine pyrophosphatase (TPPase)-positive Golgi complex in the central nervous system, it was observed that two central canals (Figs. 1 and 2) were present in the mid-thoracic region of the rat spinal cord.
